text.text:
INDU

📍 Sydney

👀 Heard the buzz about this Sri Lankan-Indian fusion joint so much so we got treated out there from family.

💥 INDU ain't your average curry house. Think Bollywood meets Brooklyn, with vibrant murals, quirky furniture, and beats that'll make your head bob like a naan in a tandoor oven.

💁🏼‍♀️Service is as warm as a chai on a monsoon night. Staff know their spices and recommend like fortune tellers with a serious case of the munchies.

🍴 Food? Buckle up, spice lovers! First, Crispy Besan Fritters danced on my tongue, sweet potato hiding under a crunchy chickpea coat, dipped in tangy chutney and creamy mayo.

The Smoked Goat Dosa was a revelation. Imagine a crispy crepe filled with melt-in-your-mouth goat, then slathered in smoky bacon jam and pomegranate.

Cured Kingfish, oh wow. Imagine the ocean and a coconut grove had a baby, dressed it in peach and puffed rice, and drizzled it with coconut heaven. Next-level fresh.

The Lamb Varuval Party Biriyani was the king of the feast. Slow-cooked lamb shoulder so tender it fell apart, nestled in fluffy rice fragrant with coconut, coriander, and mint. Sharing? If I have to…

✨ INDU is more than a meal, it's an experience. It's bold, it's playful, it's a party for your senses. So ditch the predictable curry and dive into this vibrant feast. You'll thank me later, with a napkin and a satisfied sigh.

P.S. Next time, I'm diving into the Sri Lankan Coconut Sambol and that sizzling Peppercorn Steak. See you there!

text.text: We sat down at about 7pm on a Friday night. It was our first time here but the great reviews and pan Asian menu had us curious. We waited about 10 minutes before we could order. They ran out of mango lassi so we went for the Namaste. Got our drink in about 10 minutes from ordering. Then waited another 15 minutes from our drink arriving before our food came. It looked like they might have been understaffed. We got the Namaste which was an odd drink. Didn't love it, but didn't hate it either. Would call it interesting. The tofu fritters was ok. It came with tomato sauce which we thought was a bit of a let down. Some more exciting sauce would've been better. We then had the pad Thai and sizzling noodle. I have to say, it didn't taste like pad Thai at all, more like Chinese stir fried noodles with soy sauce, which was fine if we ordered Chinese stir fry noodles. But my taste buds were expecting the tanginess, sweetness, saltiness and pungency of a pad Thai so that was a let down. The sizzling noodle was tasty, it had a satay like peanut sauce and came out sizzling, as promised. Would come back to try other dishes, but wouldn't order the pad Thai again.

The food was pretty decent but for the portions it could’ve been a bit cheaper.
The restaurant also lacked ambience in my opinion, the decoration seemed strange & the rainbow paint on the wall made it feel like it was a daycare or that the restaurant was for children.
The avocado fries were bland & weren’t anything special to be honest. But most of the dishes we had were enjoyable like the vegan chicken masala, the garlic roti & the sizzling noodles. However, the Thai green curry could be improved because the flavour didn’t feel authentic.
Overall, this is a nice restaurant, I liked the concept of it being fully vegetarian but there are many improvements that could be made. It was good to try but I won’t be rushing back anytime soon.

editorialSummary.text: Vegetarian Indian buffet dining in a cosy locale with a cinema room for movie nights.

text.text:
3.9/5*

The Feed Punchers visited a very unique punch destination, Govindas restaurant and cinema. For $28, there is an all you can eat, vegetarian buffet, incorporating fresh ingredients with a strong Indian influence.

At the start of the buffet line, there were options of white rice, brown rice, pots of soup and dahl. Next came salads, pasta and a variety of vegetable curries, which utilised predominantly; chickpeas, lentils, potato’s and tofu as the staple ingredient.

The stand out favourite for the Feed Punchers was the crispy deep fried cauliflower pakoras, which were golden and perfectly crispy. They were well paired with the tzatziki mint like sauce and the chilli chutney.

Overall, there was a great variety of fresh-vegetarian food in a buffet style. The perfect way to get a feed right before watching a movie. Thankyou Govindas!

I’d been following these guys for a while on Instagram and finally got a chance to swing by last night and try the food. The food is just as delicious as it looks. Perfectly salted, spiced and balanced.

They have some authentic Indian street dishes and some slightly elevated dishes. Most dishes were vegan and everything was vegetarian, so everyone in our entire group was accommodated for. We loved everything and cleaned our plates. The staff also recommended their black daal which is slow cooked overnight and smells divine, which I’ll have to try next time I come.

The staff were really friendly and hospitable and you can tell they are passionate about what they do. The atmosphere is very intimate and cozy and added to the overall experience.

I’d recommend this place if you’re looking for a unique Indian dining experience or craving exciting Indian street food. I’ll definitely be coming back and sharing this with more of my friends!

text.text:
4.1/5*

The Feed Punchers, after driving past the restaurant on many occasions, finally decided to make an appearance at Spice Hub, Located on Cleveland street in Surry hills. 40% off on the Eatclub app!

-The Butter chicken was creamy with nice subtle tastes of cumin and chilli powder. The chicken was cooked well, soft and juicy

-The goat masala was an incredibly tender dish, it had strong tastes of clove, cardamom and cinnamon, but lacked in its level of spice.

-The Malai Kofta was one of the favourites, it consisted of extremely soft, potato/chickpea tasting vegetarian meatballs, which were served in a buttery-curry sauce.

-The mango chicken was also one of the favourite dishes on the table. It was the best mango chicken we’ve encountered. It had a strong mango sweetness, which was complimented by a perfect creaminess and subtle spice. The chicken was, yet again, tender and soft.

-The Chilli chicken was the most spicy dish on the table, but still managed to lack in spice. It had a strong chilli powder, but was missing the extra spice.

-The Lamb Sagwala featured slow cooked lamb, which shredded on impact within the mouth and perfectly encapsulated the green-garlic- curry sauce.

-The lamb vindaloo was disappointingly mild in spice, like its neighbouring dishes, but at least it also had some very tender lamb. The sauce had a strong vinegar taste.

-The Daal had a nice spicy, creamy, tomatoey broth. It had a little kick to it, which was perfect in combination with the;

-Mixed bread basket, which featured garlic naan, cheesy naan and plain naan. The bread was fresh and soft, but the cheese and garlic were weak and insignificant in proportion.

-The Beef masala featured a soft beef, which seemed to be slow cooked. It had strong hints of coriander seed and ginger.

Overall, it was a great display of the Indian cuisine, offering some very tasty dishes. Some additional heat in the dishes would have boosted the rating. Thank-you Spice Hub!
